WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.840
How do we keep food fresh?

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:18.080
How can we reduce water usage in our daily lives?

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:23.760
How do we make trash valuable?

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:29.120
How do we innovate to make the world a better place?

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:30.559
Is what we do.

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:44.560
So at Dow, we have this graph that measures our net carbon emissions

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:46.720
of our entire product portfolio.

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:52.959
We've made very ambitious targets related to our carbon neutrality,

00:00:52.959 --> 00:00:57.520
where by 2050 we want to reach complete carbon neutrality.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:02.080
And with this graph, we can see the various projects,

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:05.599
investments, and opportunities we have to reduce our carbon footprint.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:13.919
And what's also very special about that set of goals is that it's not purely aspirational.

00:01:13.919 --> 00:01:18.000
We know we have understood the technologies required.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:25.120
We have projects in place to account for pretty much 95% of that CO2 mitigation.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:31.440
That remaining 5%, it's going to require a lot of creativity and ingenuity

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:34.160
from all different functions across Dow.

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:38.559
It's going to be up to us to figure out how to get there.

00:01:40.239 --> 00:01:43.919
I work at Dow because I love Dow's mission.

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:46.239
We touch Dow products all the time.

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:52.160
They're in food packaging, mattresses, car parts, adhesives.

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:56.000
And I like to do science to make people's lives better.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.320
We're also very ambitious because we don't want to just deliver these solutions.

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:02.879
We want to do it in a sustainable way.

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:08.160
And so all of that involves great technical and technology gaps.

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:13.360
We have a very capable and innovative bunch of researchers

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:17.839
that are able to get a lot done with just about any set of tooling that you throw out of them.

00:02:18.399 --> 00:02:26.240
However, the Posit tools, what they've enabled is an extremely low barrier to entry

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:31.600
that's allowed people who have an idea to go test that idea in a matter of minutes

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:42.080
and to be able to share the work product of exploring a concept, a Friday afternoon activity,

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:45.679
and go and share that with some of their colleagues with relative ease.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.559
So I think as scientists, we're very driven towards questioning.

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:57.039
Questioning in the sense of making sure that we're doing the right thing

00:02:57.039 --> 00:03:00.559
or that we should be pursuing the thing that we want to pursue.

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:05.360
It's our critical thinking superpower, and I think it's healthy.

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:12.639
But once we started not only talking about the vision of what these tools could do for us,

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:19.360
or started building prototypes, a lot of light bulbs started going off in people's head.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:22.320
Once you have those initial success stories,

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:28.639
and then all of these exciting ideas were on the table, the conversation was not anymore,

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:34.080
why should we do this? It's how do we do it better? How do we do it more intentionally?

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:44.320
But there is a moment when it all converges, and it clicks, and it starts flowing,

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:45.759
and now you have this rhythm.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:55.440
Since 2019, we've grown from this handful of researchers to over 300 people now have access

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:01.360
to Posit Workbench internally, and even more are using apps that are deployed on Posit Connect.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:06.800
That growth has been in part through our investment in Posit Academy,

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.880
where we're teaching people how to code using an example and a project

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:16.799
that's tailored to the work that we expect that they'll use these tools for.

00:04:16.799 --> 00:04:20.720
But also, we've been very intentional about trying to grow this community.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:23.279
We also have a citizen data science program.

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:26.480
We have more and more people asking us for these capabilities,

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:32.720
asking us for these tools that they can go use to get more value out of their data,

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:34.720
to improve their own productivity.

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:41.839
Seeing people who so often may hesitate to put on that,

00:04:41.839 --> 00:04:49.040
I'm a data scientist hat or label, but seeing what they're able to create gets me really excited.

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:52.559
The goal is really to make sure that every person in the organization

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:58.000
has some level of fluency, so they can understand and respect data generated the best possible way.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:03.200
When they are showing someone data, they will show with the highest standards of science

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:08.720
and statistics, and that they document properly all the metadata around what they generated,

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:13.440
so in the future, people can use them for advanced modeling the best possible way.

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:20.239
That connection between research and development, between science and doing good,

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:24.559
this ability to use science to make the planet a bit better,

00:05:24.559 --> 00:05:29.279
and to leave it in better conditions for my kids is extremely important to me.

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:36.799
In a typical workday, it's easy to get lost in all of those meetings,

00:05:36.799 --> 00:05:39.279
in the busy calendars, or the kids at home.

00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:43.920
It's easy to get lost in that and forget about the impact that we're going to have.

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:47.920
And it's a huge challenge that we have to face,

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:52.399
because we're literally taking what previously we've looked at as trash,

00:05:52.399 --> 00:05:54.320
and now we want to stick it back into our products.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:58.480
Not only is it something we want to do, it's something that we are doing.

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:05.679
When I think about a career at Dow, I want to be able to look back and see the,

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:11.679
maybe small, but real contribution I will have made to help us reach that.

00:06:11.679 --> 00:06:12.480
And I think we will.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:36.480
And I think we will.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:47.519
Good morning everyone.

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:50.079
Welcome to PositConf 2024.

00:06:57.119 --> 00:06:59.920
I'm so excited to see so many of you all here in the room,

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:03.119
and I know there are many more joining us online as well.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.320
A few important pieces of information.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:10.640
The number one thing you need to know about is the app that has everything that's going on,

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:12.640
regardless of whether it's our awesome speakers,

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:15.279
or some of those fun social events we have planned for you.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:19.359
Also, two important links in the app.

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:22.720
The first is in many of the sessions,

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:25.279
you'll be able to ask questions of the speakers through Slido.

00:07:25.839 --> 00:07:28.160
And if you want to engage with others online,

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:32.320
whether they're here in person or not, you can use our Discord server.

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:36.160
The first time this year, we're trying out something fun.

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:39.440
We have a little bit of a conference competition going on.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:41.519
You can enter to be in to win prizes,

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:45.920
like free tickets to next year's Conf, or sticker packs, or signed books.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:52.799
The competition is going to ask you some fun questions about you,

00:07:52.799 --> 00:07:58.000
and we're going to present those in a shiny Encordo app, of course.

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:03.359
You'll be able to see those statistics live, updating in the lounge.

00:08:03.359 --> 00:08:04.399
If you haven't heard of the lounge,

00:08:04.399 --> 00:08:06.559
you've already walked through it on the way to the keynote.

00:08:06.559 --> 00:08:10.320
But this is the best place to sit down, grab a coffee,

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:13.519
talk to our sponsors, and if you have any questions

00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:17.119
about Posit products, open source, or commercial,

00:08:17.119 --> 00:08:20.320
we'll have a bunch of folks there to answer any questions that you might have.

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:24.880
If you need to identify a Posit employee,

00:08:27.119 --> 00:08:32.320
the shirt color is a little subtler than it has been in the past,

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:38.000
but we are wearing a bluish green, and you all are wearing a greenish green.

00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:53.039
We really want everyone to feel safe and welcome at Posit Conf,

00:08:53.039 --> 00:08:54.960
so as part of your registration process,

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:57.119
you've already agreed to our code of conduct.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:01.200
If you experience any problems, or see anyone else having problems,

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:02.400
please let us know.

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:07.520
You can approach any Posit employee, you can come to the registration desk,

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:09.919
or you can email conf at posit.co.

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:18.080
We've also given you a bunch of information available on your lanyards and badges,

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:22.239
so if you want to indicate whether you'd prefer hugs,

00:09:22.239 --> 00:09:26.479
or handshakes, or no contact, you can grab one of our contact pins.

00:09:26.479 --> 00:09:29.919
We ask you to respect folks' pronouns on their badges,

00:09:29.919 --> 00:09:32.400
and finally, if you see anyone wearing a red lanyard,

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:36.080
that's an indication that I'd like to not appear in any photographs.

00:09:37.039 --> 00:09:40.880
We also have a bunch of spaces reserved if you have kids with you,

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:46.960
and they need somewhere to run around while you watch the talks on your computer.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:49.919
We have a family room on floor six.

00:09:49.919 --> 00:09:54.799
We also have a quiet zone there if you want to do some work or just chill out.

00:09:55.599 --> 00:09:57.840
On the fifth floor, we've got a meditation and prayer room,

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:02.640
and a lactation room, and every room has gender-neutral bathrooms.

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:04.479
Gender-neutral bathrooms.

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:09.919
That brings me to the most important rule of PositConf,

00:10:09.919 --> 00:10:11.440
and that is the Pac-Man rule.

00:10:12.559 --> 00:10:15.119
The Pac-Man rule is if you're standing in a group,

00:10:15.119 --> 00:10:20.559
please make sure you leave Pac-Man's mouth open so that new people can join the group.

00:10:22.239 --> 00:10:25.679
We know this is a big conference, and it can be intimidating to meet people,

00:10:25.679 --> 00:10:30.000
so at lunch today and tomorrow, we have birds of a feather stations.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.960
This makes it easy to sit down and talk to someone

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:35.840
because you've got a guaranteed shared common interest.

00:10:39.119 --> 00:10:42.880
Hopefully, you get the idea that community is important to us,

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:47.599
and community is important to us not just at Conf,

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:50.080
but to the company as a whole.

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:56.159
I wanted to take a couple of minutes of your time while I'm up here in front of you all

00:10:56.159 --> 00:11:00.239
to talk a little bit about who we are, what we do,

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:03.359
and then I'm going to introduce three of my colleagues

00:11:03.359 --> 00:11:05.760
who are going to tell you some of the particularly cool stuff

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:07.760
we've been working on in the last few months.

00:11:11.039 --> 00:11:14.400
So, to understand who we are, I think it's worth looking at our name.

00:11:15.039 --> 00:11:19.440
Now, this is not a particularly complicated name, but there are two parts,

00:11:20.479 --> 00:11:23.760
and I wanted to talk first about the second part,

00:11:23.760 --> 00:11:28.159
this PBC, or Public Benefit Corp, or B Corp.

00:11:28.159 --> 00:11:29.520
So, what is a PBC?

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:35.039
Well, if you imagine all organizations falling on some sort of continuum,

00:11:35.039 --> 00:11:36.799
on one side, you've got corporations.

00:11:37.599 --> 00:11:41.760
In the US, at least, the sole goal of an LLC

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:45.599
is to maximize shareholder revenue, shareholder value.

00:11:46.719 --> 00:11:49.440
And this is not the worst thing, right?

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:53.520
Corporations have been a tremendous economic engine

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:55.520
for the world over the last hundred years,

00:11:56.159 --> 00:11:58.479
but at Posit, we don't just want to make money,

00:11:58.479 --> 00:12:01.200
we want to do something good in the world as well.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:06.239
And one way to do something good in the world is to be a charity.

00:12:07.119 --> 00:12:11.039
But being a charity is really hard, because you have to ask people for money,

00:12:11.039 --> 00:12:13.359
and they have to give you money out of the goodness of their hearts.

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:17.679
And while there are many incredibly valuable charities,

00:12:17.679 --> 00:12:20.320
at Posit, we believe we can provide you

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:22.719
some kind of like immediate benefits as well,

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:24.799
as well as this longer-term mission

00:12:24.799 --> 00:12:28.080
to create really amazing open-source tools for data science.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.640
We can give you some tools that actually pay off right away,

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:34.559
and that you're hopefully willing to pay us for.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:36.960
And so that's why we're a PBC.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:38.960
A PBC kind of lies in the middle.

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:41.599
It has responsibilities towards its shareholders,

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:44.239
but also to its employees, to the environment,

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:47.520
and to the community.

00:12:48.479 --> 00:12:54.159
And every PBC has to have some kind of fundamental mission as well.

00:12:54.159 --> 00:12:56.000
And so this is our mission,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.280
to create free and open-source software for data science,

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:02.000
scientific research, and technical communication.

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:05.919
This mission is something that's so important to us

00:13:05.919 --> 00:13:08.880
that is fundamentally encoded in our corporate DNA.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.159
So that's the PBC side of the name.

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:15.520
Well, what about the Posit side?

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:18.719
Well, many of you know we used to be called RStudio,

00:13:18.719 --> 00:13:21.599
and that's because we mostly cared about R.

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:25.039
In the very early days, certainly we were 100% R,

00:13:25.039 --> 00:13:27.200
but it hasn't been true for a very long time,

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:29.280
because even over the last 10 years,

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:31.919
we've started to produce tools for Python,

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:34.880
and SQL, and Julia, and other languages.

00:13:35.919 --> 00:13:39.200
And you may have heard JJ and Tarif talk about our goal

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:40.719
of being a 100-year company.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:44.000
And when you think about that kind of time span,

00:13:44.719 --> 00:13:48.479
no matter how much you might love any programming language today,

00:13:48.479 --> 00:13:50.400
it seems pretty unlikely that it's going to be around

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:51.440
in 100 years' time.

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:56.080
So for Posit to exist for 100 years,

00:13:56.080 --> 00:14:00.559
we need to be willing to embrace many different languages over time.

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:03.119
The other thing we need,

00:14:03.119 --> 00:14:05.440
if we want to be around for a long time,

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:07.520
is money, and probably bags of it.

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:12.880
And that brings me to the kind of economic engine

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:14.239
at the heart of Posit,

00:14:14.239 --> 00:14:16.640
which we call the virtuous cycle.

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:21.039
So the virtuous cycle starts with us creating free

00:14:21.039 --> 00:14:22.159
and open-source software

00:14:22.159 --> 00:14:24.719
that anyone, anywhere in the world can use,

00:14:24.719 --> 00:14:25.919
regardless of means.

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:28.719
And millions of people use those tools.

00:14:29.679 --> 00:14:32.400
And then some of those people go on to join organizations,

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:36.159
larger organizations that have kind of special needs,

00:14:36.159 --> 00:14:38.400
and that leads them to our commercial products.

00:14:39.359 --> 00:14:41.039
And by buying our commercial products,

00:14:41.039 --> 00:14:43.760
you both give us the money to support further investment

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:45.679
in free and open-source software,

00:14:45.679 --> 00:14:47.599
but you also give us data.

00:14:47.599 --> 00:14:51.440
Data about what are the challenges facing data sciences today

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:55.919
that we can solve in both our open-source tools

00:14:55.919 --> 00:14:57.119
and our commercial tools.

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:01.520
So the way we kind of think a little,

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:04.960
kind of think about the split between the free and the paid

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:10.239
is generally the tools we provide for doing data science are free.

00:15:10.239 --> 00:15:12.880
So that's tools like the Tidyverse and Tidymodels

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:14.400
for doing data science in R

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:17.760
or many of the hundreds of R packages that we maintain.

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:20.320
It's also true for tools like Shiny,

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:23.599
which allow you to create interactive apps for R and Python,

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:27.359
or Korto, which allow you to create data-driven documents

00:15:27.359 --> 00:15:30.640
and using R and Python and Julia and other languages.

00:15:32.719 --> 00:15:36.080
When you want to bring those tools into your organization,

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:38.640
that's where our commercial tools come into play.

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:43.520
Because large organizations have special needs.

00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:46.880
They have needs for things like authentication and monitoring,

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:50.559
security, for scaling and tuning and data governance.

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:55.200
And we also charge for products that live in the cloud,

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.679
regardless of whether those are our own products,

00:15:57.679 --> 00:16:00.239
like Shiny Apps IO or Posit Cloud,

00:16:00.799 --> 00:16:04.159
or tools from our partners like Databricks and Snowflake,

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:09.840
or for generalized compute services like AWS or Azure

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:11.760
or Google's Compute Platform.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.440
So at the heart of Posit, there are really three beliefs.

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:23.840
First of all, we believe in open source,

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:28.719
that the era of using proprietary software to do data science is over.

00:16:29.840 --> 00:16:32.000
That open source provides such a benefit,

00:16:32.719 --> 00:16:34.880
is such a great way of doing software development,

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:36.719
because it brings together expertise

00:16:36.719 --> 00:16:38.719
from many, many people all around the world.

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:43.200
We also believe in code,

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:45.679
and clearly not getting our fonts correct.

00:16:49.039 --> 00:16:52.239
We believe if you're doing data science every day,

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:55.359
that the benefits of learning to code

00:16:55.359 --> 00:16:58.239
massively outweigh the costs of learning to code.

00:16:59.679 --> 00:17:01.520
Now, this is certainly not true for everyone, right?

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:04.160
Not everyone uses data science every day,

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:06.319
and there's a bunch of different user interfaces

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:08.640
that might appeal to different types of people.

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:10.640
But fundamentally, what we believe in

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:12.800
and the audience that we want to serve

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:14.880
are people who write code.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:19.199
And so what we want to do is take open source,

00:17:19.199 --> 00:17:20.959
code-first data science,

00:17:20.959 --> 00:17:23.119
and make it ready for the enterprise,

00:17:23.119 --> 00:17:25.040
so that you can take the same tools

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:28.400
that you used for free when you're learning,

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.160
and regardless of whether you join

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:32.400
a 10-person little business

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:35.359
or a 100,000-person massive organization,

00:17:35.359 --> 00:17:36.640
you can take those tools

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:38.479
and continue to use them effectively.

00:17:40.319 --> 00:17:41.520
So what are those tools?

00:17:42.959 --> 00:17:45.199
Well, the first one, and to my mind at least,

00:17:45.199 --> 00:17:46.880
the most important, is Kinect,

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:51.280
because it connects data scientists to decision makers.

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:54.160
Kinect makes it easy to deploy

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:57.920
whatever you create as a data scientist

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.160
regardless of whether that's a Shiny app

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:02.719
or a Flask API or a Cordo document

00:18:02.719 --> 00:18:04.479
or an R Markdown document,

00:18:04.479 --> 00:18:06.479
and get that out of your hands

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:07.920
and into the hands of the people,

00:18:08.479 --> 00:18:10.479
the decision makers in your organization.

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:16.000
Posit Workbench is about helping data scientists,

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.359
teams of data scientists,

00:18:17.359 --> 00:18:19.280
collaborate using shared compute

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:22.239
and providing seamless authorization

00:18:22.239 --> 00:18:23.680
and authentication

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:26.400
so you can just get the data you need

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:28.640
without having to fuss around

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:30.479
trying to find the right database driver

00:18:30.479 --> 00:18:31.920
or randomly Google

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:34.400
and finding Stack Overflow answers from five years ago.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:37.439
And Workbench helps you do that

00:18:37.439 --> 00:18:39.439
regardless of whether you use RStudio

00:18:39.439 --> 00:18:43.040
or JupyterLab, Jupyter Notebooks, or VS Code.

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:46.880
Posit Package Manager is all about

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:50.800
bringing open-source R packages and Python packages

00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:54.400
into the walled garden of your IT organization

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:57.359
so that your IT folks don't need to worry

00:18:57.359 --> 00:19:00.319
about you installing random code from the internet

00:19:00.319 --> 00:19:02.880
and you can still use all of the tools that you're used to.

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:07.199
As James mentioned in the intro video,

00:19:07.199 --> 00:19:10.880
Posit Academy is all about creating new data scientists

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:14.959
using a project-based apprenticeship program

00:19:14.959 --> 00:19:17.599
that brings together data scientist mentors

00:19:17.599 --> 00:19:20.719
from Posit with mentors inside your organization

00:19:20.719 --> 00:19:23.920
so that folks learn the way that you all do data science.

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:27.119
And then finally, we have Posit Cloud,

00:19:27.119 --> 00:19:29.760
which solves problems for organizations,

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:32.560
often small and medium businesses and education,

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:35.040
that don't want to run their own IT organization.

00:19:35.040 --> 00:19:37.439
It allows you to compute in the cloud

00:19:37.439 --> 00:19:39.280
and publish your results to share

00:19:39.280 --> 00:19:41.040
without having to have a big team of people

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:43.599
in your organization running your own hardware.

00:19:47.199 --> 00:19:49.040
So let's Posit PBC.

00:19:49.199 --> 00:19:53.199
We are a company that has a mission.

00:19:53.199 --> 00:19:56.640
We want to make free and open-source software

00:19:56.640 --> 00:19:59.520
to make data science, scientific communication,

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:01.280
and technical publishing better.

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:04.400
And we do that by selling products

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:06.800
that hopefully also make your lives better

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:08.959
inside companies as well.

00:20:08.959 --> 00:20:11.199
So this is a mission that really aligns

00:20:11.199 --> 00:20:13.839
with my personal mission and is one of the reasons

00:20:13.839 --> 00:20:16.400
that I joined our studio, I joined Posit,

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:17.599
well, I joined our team,

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:19.599
I joined Posit, well, I joined our studio,

00:20:19.599 --> 00:20:21.520
and I continue to work at Posit today.

