00:22:26.959 --> 00:22:28.719
I'm here today to talk about two things

00:22:28.719 --> 00:22:31.199
that the Corto team has been working on in the last year.

00:22:32.479 --> 00:22:34.400
And the first comes from looking back,

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:37.040
looking back to the R Markdown ecosystem

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:39.040
and seeing what was missing in Corto.

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:41.359
And that was dashboards.

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:44.640
So Corto dashboards are an HTML format

00:22:45.199 --> 00:22:49.680
designed for the full page layout of plots and tables and values.

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:51.920
And this is one I found out out in the wild,

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:53.280
somebody already using it

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:55.439
for the Shelby County Department of Housing.

00:22:57.199 --> 00:23:00.640
The fundamental unit in a Corto dashboard is a card.

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:04.400
And these cards get laid out in rows and columns.

00:23:06.479 --> 00:23:08.719
What does it look like to build a Corto dashboard?

00:23:08.719 --> 00:23:10.800
Take a look at this HTML document.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:14.479
It's got a table, it's got a plot, it's got a map.

00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:18.160
What does it take to turn that into a dashboard?

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:23.520
Well, you simply swap out format HTML for format dashboard.

00:23:24.479 --> 00:23:28.000
All of the computational outputs are going to get put into cards

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.640
and then those cards get laid out on the page.

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:34.959
By default, that happens in a single column.

00:23:34.959 --> 00:23:36.959
You can see they're all stacked on top of each other.

00:23:36.959 --> 00:23:39.439
What happens if you want a two-row layout?

00:23:39.439 --> 00:23:43.040
All you have to do is add two markdown headings.

00:23:43.599 --> 00:23:44.640
It's as simple as that.

00:23:46.079 --> 00:23:48.319
You can put anything in a Corto dashboard

00:23:48.319 --> 00:23:50.719
that you could normally put in a Corto document.

00:23:51.359 --> 00:23:54.319
But there are some specific dashboard components.

00:23:54.319 --> 00:23:56.800
So, for example, there are these value boxes.

00:23:57.359 --> 00:24:00.000
These are ways to have a single value

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
but in a visually attractive way.

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:05.119
And there is this idea of input panels,

00:24:05.359 --> 00:24:08.319
which is a way to group together interactive inputs

00:24:08.319 --> 00:24:10.400
into sidebars or toolbars.

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:15.280
You can also add interactivity in a Corto dashboard

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:18.400
any way you can in a Corto document,

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:21.520
including native support for observable JS.

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:25.199
You can use frameworks like Leaflet and Plotly and 3JS

00:24:25.199 --> 00:24:28.880
through HTML widgets in R and Jupyter widgets in Python.

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:31.520
And, of course, you can use Shiny.

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:34.319
You can add Shiny and Shiny for Python inputs

00:24:35.199 --> 00:24:37.760
and outputs directly in code cells.

00:24:39.920 --> 00:24:41.520
You can learn more about dashboards

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:44.079
by heading to corto.org and checking out our guide.

00:24:45.199 --> 00:24:48.079
If you want to see a dashboard in action at Conf,

00:24:48.079 --> 00:24:50.719
head to the It's Not R or Python session.

00:24:50.719 --> 00:24:52.160
It's R and Python.

00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:54.239
You can hear Nick Crane and Alenka Frum

00:24:54.239 --> 00:24:55.680
talk about a dashboard they've built

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.800
that's got both Python and R components.

