and disabled by too much choice.

00:25:40.160 --> 00:25:43.920
The next thing I want to talk about is the future.

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:45.199
The next thing I want to talk about

00:25:45.199 --> 00:25:47.119
comes from looking towards the future.

00:25:48.239 --> 00:25:51.040
In particular, the future of PDF.

00:25:52.719 --> 00:25:55.520
Let me tell you about our PBC report.

00:25:56.079 --> 00:25:58.640
This is a report that Posit makes every two years

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:02.160
that tracks our progress toward our mission.

00:26:03.439 --> 00:26:06.000
And it is primarily a PDF document.

00:26:07.520 --> 00:26:09.280
Here's the cover of that document.

00:26:09.839 --> 00:26:11.280
Inside, there's some pages

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:13.760
that have this dark blue hex background.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:15.599
There's some pages that have a white background

00:26:15.599 --> 00:26:17.280
but with some full bleed photos.

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:19.119
Text is laid out in two columns.

00:26:19.119 --> 00:26:21.439
Some pages have a banner at the top.

00:26:21.439 --> 00:26:22.479
There's plots in there.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.040
This year, we made that report with Corto.

00:26:28.719 --> 00:26:30.959
And if you've made PDFs with Corto before,

00:26:30.959 --> 00:26:34.959
you know that they go through LaTeX on that journey.

00:26:34.959 --> 00:26:38.400
But we did not make this report by going through LaTeX.

00:26:39.359 --> 00:26:40.719
We used Typed.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:45.760
Typed is a new open source framework for producing PDFs.

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:48.239
And it's already supported by Corto.

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:53.520
To use Typed, you simply swap out format PDF for format Typed.

00:26:55.520 --> 00:26:57.599
We think Typed is the future of PDF

00:26:57.599 --> 00:27:00.479
because it's really easy to get started.

00:27:00.479 --> 00:27:02.079
Corto bundles Typed,

00:27:02.079 --> 00:27:04.479
so there's no separate install to manage.

00:27:05.599 --> 00:27:07.280
You can do it today.

00:27:09.119 --> 00:27:10.319
Typed is really fast.

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:13.119
So rendering a PDF via Typed

00:27:13.119 --> 00:27:15.680
is much faster than rendering a PDF via LaTeX.

00:27:17.839 --> 00:27:19.199
We think it's easier to learn.

00:27:19.199 --> 00:27:22.400
There's great documentation on the Typed site.

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:24.640
And the syntax feels a lot more familiar

00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:26.160
to people that are coming from languages

00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:27.760
like R or Python or Julia.

00:27:28.719 --> 00:27:31.199
And it's very customizable.

00:27:31.199 --> 00:27:33.599
So our report being an example of that.

00:27:33.599 --> 00:27:35.520
It took a little work to get that customization,

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:38.000
but you can produce really beautiful documents.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:41.760
So we think it's the future of PDF.

00:27:41.760 --> 00:27:44.479
It maybe isn't quite the present of PDF.

00:27:44.479 --> 00:27:45.920
Typed is still developing,

00:27:45.920 --> 00:27:48.719
and our support in Corto is still developing too.

00:27:49.839 --> 00:27:52.079
But I do want to show you something really cool

00:27:52.079 --> 00:27:53.920
you can do in Typed right now.

00:27:55.359 --> 00:27:56.400
So take a look at this table.

00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:57.920
This is an HTML table.

00:27:58.479 --> 00:28:00.959
It's built using the GreatTables package in Python.

00:28:00.959 --> 00:28:03.839
And an example from Grant Chalmers.

00:28:03.839 --> 00:28:05.839
It's on the GreatTables documentation site.

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:09.680
And I think it's a beautiful table.

00:28:11.119 --> 00:28:14.160
And GreatTables and GT and a lot of table packages

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:17.839
really focus on absolutely beautiful HTML output.

00:28:18.880 --> 00:28:21.760
So what happens if you switch to Typed?

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:24.640
Well, behind the scenes,

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:26.560
Corto takes all the CSS

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:29.280
that makes that HTML table really beautiful,

00:28:29.920 --> 00:28:32.800
and it converts it to Typed properties.

00:28:33.439 --> 00:28:36.560
And what that means is when you get your PDF out,

00:28:36.560 --> 00:28:40.560
that table looks just as good as it did in HTML,

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:41.839
but now it's in a PDF.

00:28:43.439 --> 00:28:46.560
And not only that, like Typed is sort of good enough

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:48.479
to know that, hey, this table's pretty long.

00:28:48.479 --> 00:28:50.479
It's not going to fit on one page.

00:28:50.479 --> 00:28:52.079
I'll break it over two pages,

00:28:52.079 --> 00:28:53.599
and I'll repeat the headers and footers

00:28:53.599 --> 00:28:55.760
and make it all just work for you.

00:28:56.479 --> 00:28:57.119
It's really cool.

00:28:59.599 --> 00:29:01.119
The last thing I wanted to talk about

00:29:01.119 --> 00:29:03.040
is not what we've been working on,

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:04.880
but what other people have been working on

00:29:05.520 --> 00:29:07.599
that enhances Corto for everyone.

00:29:11.199 --> 00:29:13.439
So when Corto was built, it was great

00:29:13.439 --> 00:29:15.359
because it brought all these features of R

00:29:15.359 --> 00:29:17.280
marked down to Python users

00:29:17.280 --> 00:29:19.760
without requiring them to install R.

00:29:20.319 --> 00:29:22.160
But if you were a Julia user,

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:23.680
the first thing you would see is,

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:25.599
hey, you need to install Jupyter,

00:29:25.599 --> 00:29:26.800
and that's a Python thing.

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:29.680
That is no longer true.

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:31.599
There is a native Julia engine,

00:29:31.599 --> 00:29:33.760
so if you want to run Julia code

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:36.719
without having to have an R install or a Python install,

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:38.319
you can now do that.

00:29:38.319 --> 00:29:40.640
And that was an entirely external contribution

00:29:41.439 --> 00:29:42.719
from Julius Krumbegel.

00:29:44.079 --> 00:29:46.239
The other contributions I want to talk about

00:29:46.239 --> 00:29:47.680
come in the form of extensions.

00:29:49.199 --> 00:29:50.560
And there are Corto extensions

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:52.160
to add QR codes to your slide,

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:53.280
and there are Corto extensions

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:55.199
to add countdowns to your slide.

00:29:55.199 --> 00:29:56.640
There's already a Corto extension

00:29:56.640 --> 00:29:59.520
that gives you Tufti-style output via types.

00:30:00.719 --> 00:30:02.880
And there are so many extensions

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:04.959
that you should check out this other contribution.

00:30:06.239 --> 00:30:08.560
This is a Corto extension listing

00:30:08.560 --> 00:30:10.479
built by Mikhail Kanwe.

00:30:11.359 --> 00:30:14.079
And it's a great place to go to see

00:30:14.079 --> 00:30:15.839
what's new in the extension world

00:30:15.839 --> 00:30:17.920
and what's popular in the extension world.

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:21.680
If you want to see some Corto extensions here at Conf,

00:30:22.319 --> 00:30:24.959
you can see James Goldie talking about an extension

00:30:24.959 --> 00:30:27.760
he's built to bring the power of Svelte graphics

00:30:27.760 --> 00:30:28.719
to Corto documents.

00:30:29.439 --> 00:30:31.680
And you can also hear Andrew Bray

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:34.239
talk about an extension he's worked on with James

00:30:34.239 --> 00:30:37.199
to bring scroll retelling to Corto documents.

00:30:39.280 --> 00:30:41.359
If I haven't put enough on your schedule already,

00:30:42.319 --> 00:30:46.000
you can find the Corto team in the lounge today at noon.

00:30:48.640 --> 00:30:50.400
It's been an absolute pleasure

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:52.319
telling you what we've been working on

00:30:52.319 --> 00:30:54.000
and showing what you've been working on.

00:30:54.959 --> 00:30:57.920
And I hope that together we can keep Corto

00:30:57.920 --> 00:30:59.920
as the gift that keeps on giving.

