Posit's mission of making great open source software

00:31:27.199 --> 00:31:28.319
really resonates with me.

00:31:29.359 --> 00:31:31.680
I've been working for Posit for about two years

00:31:31.680 --> 00:31:34.160
and I'm still really excited to tell people that.

00:31:34.160 --> 00:31:37.199
Posit's mission of making great open source software

00:31:37.359 --> 00:31:38.400
really resonates with me.

00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:41.439
I've been making open source software for over 10 years now.

00:31:41.439 --> 00:31:44.959
I started in research software developing for HPC

00:31:46.239 --> 00:31:49.040
and over that time my approach to open source

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:51.599
has always been no matter what you do,

00:31:51.599 --> 00:31:53.359
no matter what decisions I make,

00:31:53.359 --> 00:31:55.839
they must always be in the interest of the user.

00:31:56.880 --> 00:31:58.959
And it was that philosophy that originally led me

00:31:58.959 --> 00:31:59.920
to create WebR.

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:02.959
At the time I was supporting a group of students

00:32:02.959 --> 00:32:05.599
who were remote up and down the UK

00:32:05.599 --> 00:32:08.079
and we needed to evaluate R code

00:32:08.079 --> 00:32:10.400
in a consistent environment and capture those results.

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:13.920
To me this felt like the best solution for the job.

00:32:15.599 --> 00:32:17.439
If you've not seen WebR before,

00:32:17.439 --> 00:32:20.160
here's an example of a WebR application.

00:32:20.160 --> 00:32:21.920
It's a website you can visit

00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:24.959
and when you do an R console pops up

00:32:24.959 --> 00:32:27.920
and you can type code in and you can do visualizations

00:32:27.920 --> 00:32:29.520
and you can really experiment with R

00:32:30.079 --> 00:32:31.520
in a very easy way, very quickly.

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:35.359
This is really great for new users of R

00:32:35.359 --> 00:32:37.920
who don't have something like RStudio installed.

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:39.760
And Hadley earlier talked about the idea

00:32:39.760 --> 00:32:41.680
of code first data science.

00:32:41.680 --> 00:32:44.400
What could be more code first than opening a web browser

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:45.680
and typing in some R code?

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:47.760
So how does this work?

00:32:48.800 --> 00:32:51.199
The main technology is called WebAssembly

00:32:52.079 --> 00:32:53.359
and what WebAssembly is,

00:32:53.359 --> 00:32:55.520
is a portable binary code format.

00:32:55.520 --> 00:32:56.479
So what does that mean?

00:32:58.000 --> 00:32:59.520
Really this just means that

00:32:59.520 --> 00:33:01.359
if you take a piece of software and compile it,

00:33:01.359 --> 00:33:04.079
you get a big list of instructions to execute.

00:33:04.079 --> 00:33:05.359
The word portable here

00:33:05.359 --> 00:33:07.040
just means that those instructions,

00:33:07.040 --> 00:33:10.079
the binary is the same on every machine.

00:33:10.079 --> 00:33:12.719
And that's done by running that binary inside a web browser.

00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:15.199
It's really designed to run

00:33:15.199 --> 00:33:17.040
high performance applications in this way.

00:33:17.839 --> 00:33:20.800
It does work with most modern web browsers on many devices.

00:33:22.160 --> 00:33:26.560
And one of the things it's really great at is security

00:33:26.560 --> 00:33:28.319
because it's really designed to run on the web.

00:33:28.880 --> 00:33:31.760
It runs your code in a containerized sandbox environment.

00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:34.640
In a web browser,

00:33:34.640 --> 00:33:37.920
you interact with WebAssembly through JavaScript

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:40.319
and that has positives and negatives.

00:33:41.439 --> 00:33:44.719
It means that WebR itself is a JavaScript application.

00:33:44.719 --> 00:33:46.400
So you need to write JavaScript to use it.

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:49.119
And a positive of that is that

00:33:49.119 --> 00:33:51.359
it means it works great with other web technologies.

00:33:52.079 --> 00:33:53.439
A downside of that is that

00:33:53.439 --> 00:33:56.079
you probably don't love writing JavaScript code.

00:33:56.719 --> 00:33:57.839
At least not in the same way

00:33:57.839 --> 00:34:00.000
that the people in front of me love writing R code

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:01.520
or they love writing Python code.

00:34:02.719 --> 00:34:03.599
So for that reason,

00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:06.959
in addition to working on WebR,

00:34:06.959 --> 00:34:11.840
we produce tools built upon WebR to make your job easier.

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:14.719
Tools like ShinyLive.

00:34:15.840 --> 00:34:17.520
At PositConf last year,

00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:20.719
Joe Tang had a talk introducing ShinyLive for R

00:34:20.719 --> 00:34:22.320
built upon the WebR technology.

00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:25.679
And over the years since then,

00:34:25.679 --> 00:34:27.840
we've been continuing to update the system.

00:34:27.840 --> 00:34:29.120
There's been several releases.

00:34:29.120 --> 00:34:33.439
And you can use ShinyLive now in a web browser

00:34:33.439 --> 00:34:36.159
to interact with live Shiny examples.

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:39.439
You can export existing apps using an R package.

00:34:40.239 --> 00:34:41.840
Or you can use a Quota extension

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:43.439
to embed Shiny applications

00:34:43.439 --> 00:34:45.600
directly into your Quota documents.

00:34:46.639 --> 00:34:48.479
Again, the website example is great.

00:34:48.479 --> 00:34:51.439
You can go on to a URL and type some Shiny code

00:34:51.439 --> 00:34:52.320
and it just appears.

00:34:53.439 --> 00:34:56.239
And I've actually seen this used at workshops

00:34:56.239 --> 00:34:57.919
to teach people how to use Shiny

00:34:57.919 --> 00:34:59.040
and to share examples.

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:04.479
And that takes me on to one of the demographics

00:35:04.479 --> 00:35:06.719
that have really taken ShinyLive and run with it.

00:35:06.719 --> 00:35:10.080
And that's the demographic of educational content educators.

00:35:10.879 --> 00:35:13.840
They've really embraced the idea

00:35:13.840 --> 00:35:16.479
of WebAssembly-powered educational content.

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:18.560
And for that reason,

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:19.439
we thought to ourselves,

00:35:19.439 --> 00:35:21.040
well, is there more we can do?

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:23.919
Can we get more WebAssembly into Quota documents?

00:35:25.040 --> 00:35:26.959
And the answer to that is yes.

00:35:26.959 --> 00:35:29.040
And I've been working on a new extension

00:35:29.679 --> 00:35:31.360
for Quota over the last six months.

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:35.760
And we're calling it Quota Live.

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:41.840
Quota Live is a way to get interactive code examples

00:35:41.840 --> 00:35:44.639
in R in your Quota documents.

00:35:44.639 --> 00:35:46.719
You can directly interact with that code

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:49.439
and you can create code exercises

00:35:49.439 --> 00:35:51.280
so that if you're an educator,

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:53.439
you can create very easy ways

00:35:53.439 --> 00:35:55.919
for students to interact with your code

00:35:56.560 --> 00:35:58.000
and get quality feedback.

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:03.040
We've designed Quota Live to be really, really easy

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:05.040
to use both for authors

00:36:05.040 --> 00:36:06.639
and for the students and learners.

00:36:08.479 --> 00:36:09.360
So what does it look like?

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:11.679
So let's say you have a Quota document

00:36:11.679 --> 00:36:12.800
and it looks a bit like this.

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:14.399
You've got some R code

00:36:14.399 --> 00:36:15.919
and it's producing a visualization.

00:36:15.919 --> 00:36:17.919
Here we have some air quality data

00:36:17.919 --> 00:36:19.439
from 1970s New York

00:36:20.080 --> 00:36:21.679
and it's plotting some temperatures

00:36:21.679 --> 00:36:22.639
and some ozone levels.

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:25.199
Now, let's say you want to turn this

00:36:25.199 --> 00:36:26.800
into an interactive example.

00:36:26.800 --> 00:36:28.800
Much like in Charlotte's examples,

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:31.280
you change the format into a live format

00:36:32.159 --> 00:36:34.320
and you change your R block into a web R block.

00:36:35.040 --> 00:36:37.120
And if you have the Quota Live extension installed,

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:37.600
that's it.

00:36:37.600 --> 00:36:38.399
You do nothing else.

00:36:38.399 --> 00:36:39.600
It just, it works.

00:36:41.040 --> 00:36:44.239
You can see the output looks pretty much identical.

00:36:44.239 --> 00:36:45.120
That's by design.

00:36:45.679 --> 00:36:47.120
And the only real difference

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:49.439
is that your source code above your output

00:36:49.439 --> 00:36:50.959
is now an editable code block

00:36:51.600 --> 00:36:52.719
that you can interact with

00:36:52.719 --> 00:36:54.479
and click the buttons to rerun your code.

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:56.879
Now, this is great for students

00:36:56.879 --> 00:37:00.320
because someone who's interacting

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:02.159
with this content for the first time

00:37:02.159 --> 00:37:03.439
may be interested.

00:37:03.439 --> 00:37:04.399
They want to know more.

00:37:04.399 --> 00:37:06.159
They want to play with this example.

00:37:06.159 --> 00:37:07.919
Previously, they would have to copy that code

00:37:07.919 --> 00:37:08.959
and open our studio

00:37:08.959 --> 00:37:10.639
and switch to a different window.

00:37:10.639 --> 00:37:13.360
But now they can literally just change the code

00:37:13.360 --> 00:37:15.040
to plot wind instead of temperature,

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:15.679
hit the button,

00:37:15.679 --> 00:37:17.360
and it's there in the same page

00:37:17.360 --> 00:37:18.399
inside their document.

00:37:20.159 --> 00:37:21.040
By the way,

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:23.520
one of the things I'm really excited about this

00:37:23.520 --> 00:37:25.760
is that those are no longer pictures

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:27.919
that are distributed with your document.

00:37:27.919 --> 00:37:30.080
They're generated dynamically on the fly

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:31.600
every time you open that document.

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:35.600
That means they're kind of reproducible by default, right?

00:37:35.600 --> 00:37:38.560
Because the fact that you can see that image at all

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:40.320
means the R code in your document

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:42.000
has executed successfully

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:43.439
and produced some output.

00:37:46.719 --> 00:37:47.600
If you're an educator

00:37:47.600 --> 00:37:50.719
and you want to augment these code examples

00:37:50.719 --> 00:37:51.840
into an exercise,

00:37:51.840 --> 00:37:53.439
you give it an exercise label.

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:54.879
At that point,

00:37:54.879 --> 00:37:56.479
you can then add things

00:37:56.479 --> 00:37:59.760
to make that exercise more and more interactive.

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:00.560
Here's an example

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:03.280
where we're asking a student to plot some data, right?

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:05.360
And what we're going to do

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:07.760
is we're going to augment that with some setup code.

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:09.679
So we create another WebR block.

00:38:09.679 --> 00:38:11.360
We tell it it's a setup block

00:38:11.360 --> 00:38:13.199
and this is the exercise that it's linked to.

00:38:14.399 --> 00:38:15.040
And what we've done

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:17.280
is we've set up that data set for the students

00:38:17.280 --> 00:38:18.639
so they don't have to worry about it.

00:38:18.639 --> 00:38:20.399
They don't have to worry about loading that data.

00:38:20.399 --> 00:38:21.600
It's just there.

00:38:21.600 --> 00:38:24.159
They can just directly answer that question

00:38:24.159 --> 00:38:25.760
without having to worry about the extra parts.

00:38:25.760 --> 00:38:26.879
And that's because a setup block

00:38:26.879 --> 00:38:28.479
will run automatically

00:38:28.479 --> 00:38:31.120
every time when that student hits the run button.

00:38:33.679 --> 00:38:35.520
So let's say the student tries to run their code.

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:36.719
They see, okay, there's a blank.

00:38:36.719 --> 00:38:37.919
I need to answer this question.

00:38:38.479 --> 00:38:39.679
But they're struggling.

00:38:39.679 --> 00:38:40.399
They're new to this.

00:38:40.399 --> 00:38:41.600
They're not quite sure what's going on.

00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:42.159
Can we help?

00:38:43.280 --> 00:38:44.239
Well, we could add a hint

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:46.879
and we do that using a quarter block.

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:49.520
Here's a quarter block with the class hint

00:38:49.520 --> 00:38:51.280
and we've, again, linked it to our exercise

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:53.280
using that same shared exercise label.

00:38:54.800 --> 00:38:56.479
Inside there, you can write your hint

00:38:56.479 --> 00:38:57.760
and you'll notice it's not added

00:38:57.760 --> 00:38:59.120
to the document straight away.

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:01.840
Instead, QuartoLive adds a button

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:03.600
to the exercise saying hint

00:39:03.600 --> 00:39:04.800
and when the student clicks it,

00:39:05.439 --> 00:39:07.760
then they get the hint text containing your block.

00:39:08.399 --> 00:39:09.679
And if the student's still struggling,

00:39:09.679 --> 00:39:11.760
you can do the same thing with a solution block.

00:39:11.760 --> 00:39:14.080
You can write your Quarto code inside a solution block

00:39:14.080 --> 00:39:15.840
and when the student hits that button,

00:39:15.840 --> 00:39:17.600
they see that solution text.

00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:19.760
What's really great about this

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:21.840
is that this is just Quarto syntax.

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:23.280
There's nothing new here.

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:27.040
All of the tools that you know how to write in Quarto

00:39:27.040 --> 00:39:30.479
to make great content will work inside these blocks.

00:39:30.479 --> 00:39:32.000
Tools like call-out blocks,

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:33.520
tools like collapsible panels,

00:39:35.919 --> 00:39:38.000
syntax highlighted code blocks,

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.080
code annotations to really explain

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:41.520
how a piece of code works.

00:39:41.520 --> 00:39:44.080
All of these things work inside a solution block

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:44.639
and a hint block.

00:39:44.639 --> 00:39:46.800
So you can make all of these tools

00:39:46.800 --> 00:39:48.560
work with your exercises straight away.

00:39:49.919 --> 00:39:51.520
Now that the student has seen the solution,

00:39:51.520 --> 00:39:52.959
they can then obviously continue

00:39:52.959 --> 00:39:55.280
to interact with the code exercise,

00:39:56.399 --> 00:39:57.679
paste in that code and run it

00:39:57.679 --> 00:39:59.840
and ah, I'd recognize that logo anyway.

00:40:02.879 --> 00:40:05.280
A nice, well, maybe not so nice,

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:10.080
an interesting thing about educational content

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:13.199
is that lots of students now

00:40:13.199 --> 00:40:16.080
are not really interacting with this content

00:40:16.080 --> 00:40:18.639
using a laptop or a desktop computer

00:40:18.639 --> 00:40:19.360
with a big screen.

00:40:19.919 --> 00:40:21.679
They're interacting with this content

00:40:21.679 --> 00:40:22.879
on screens that look more like this.

00:40:24.399 --> 00:40:26.879
And we've really designed WebR

00:40:26.879 --> 00:40:28.560
to work as best as it can

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:30.000
on these constrained devices

00:40:30.719 --> 00:40:32.959
so that all those tools like visualizing

00:40:32.959 --> 00:40:34.560
and plotting and producing graphics,

00:40:34.560 --> 00:40:39.520
they work on something like a mobile phone or tablet,

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:41.919
even if these devices themselves

00:40:41.919 --> 00:40:44.560
can't install something like R or RStudio.

00:40:45.199 --> 00:40:47.199
And much in the same way that Quarto itself

00:40:47.199 --> 00:40:50.000
resizes very nicely on these small screens,

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.159
Quarto Live has again also been designed

00:40:52.159 --> 00:40:53.760
so that these exercises work well

00:40:53.760 --> 00:40:54.800
in these kind of environments.

00:40:55.600 --> 00:40:57.280
The idea here is that

00:40:57.280 --> 00:41:00.080
we want to be able to support education for any user,

00:41:00.080 --> 00:41:02.080
no matter what kind of device they're using.

00:41:03.919 --> 00:41:05.280
Some more quick examples of the things

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:06.639
you can do with Quarto Live.

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:10.479
If you've ever used the LearnR or GradeThis system,

00:41:10.479 --> 00:41:12.639
you may be interested in writing algorithms

00:41:12.639 --> 00:41:14.159
to grade students' code.

00:41:14.879 --> 00:41:15.439
You can do that.

00:41:15.439 --> 00:41:18.159
Here's an example where we ask students

00:41:18.159 --> 00:41:20.000
to do some filtering and summarizing

00:41:21.760 --> 00:41:23.919
of some customer reviews of a cat bed.

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:26.560
And if the student makes a mistake,

00:41:26.560 --> 00:41:28.959
we can give some encouraging feedback to say,

00:41:28.959 --> 00:41:30.879
you know, try again, you're almost there.

00:41:31.679 --> 00:41:33.120
If the student gets the answer right,

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:35.679
we can give some celebratory feedback

00:41:36.959 --> 00:41:37.760
to say, great job.

00:41:39.360 --> 00:41:41.600
What's really great about this

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:44.399
is that the R code that the student writes

00:41:44.399 --> 00:41:46.080
is really being evaluated.

00:41:46.080 --> 00:41:47.520
And your grading algorithms

00:41:47.520 --> 00:41:48.800
are also really being evaluated.

00:41:48.800 --> 00:41:50.479
And then these are all written in R code.

00:41:50.479 --> 00:41:52.399
So you can catch certain mistakes

00:41:52.399 --> 00:41:53.840
that you know students are going to make.

00:41:54.560 --> 00:41:56.239
Say, you know students are going to use

00:41:56.239 --> 00:41:58.879
a double ampersand here when they should use one.

00:41:58.879 --> 00:42:00.959
In addition to the error text from R,

00:42:00.959 --> 00:42:02.959
which may not be entirely clear

00:42:02.959 --> 00:42:04.879
to a new student what that means,

00:42:04.879 --> 00:42:07.040
you can add targeted feedback to say,

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:08.479
oh, this is what you've done wrong

00:42:08.479 --> 00:42:09.679
and this is how you can fix it.

00:42:10.879 --> 00:42:12.560
The tools that make this work

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:15.600
are very dynamic and very general.

00:42:15.600 --> 00:42:17.360
They're not just designed to work

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:18.959
with exercises like this.

00:42:18.959 --> 00:42:20.399
In a Quarter Live document,

00:42:21.280 --> 00:42:23.840
you can use observable JS inputs

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:25.520
with WebAssembly blocks

00:42:25.520 --> 00:42:28.239
to create a dashboard-like experience

00:42:28.959 --> 00:42:30.719
deployed to some kind of static server,

00:42:30.719 --> 00:42:32.000
something like GitHub Pages,

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:33.360
something like Quarter Pub.

00:42:33.360 --> 00:42:35.120
Again, these tools that authors

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:36.320
already know how to use,

00:42:37.120 --> 00:42:39.040
they can deploy to these places

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:41.360
without having to become an expert in DevOps,

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:42.959
learn how to run a Shiny server

00:42:42.959 --> 00:42:45.360
and manage these Shiny applications.

00:42:45.360 --> 00:42:46.959
Instead, you can just fire and forget.

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:50.159
So, that's Quarter Live.

00:42:50.959 --> 00:42:52.320
It was released last week.

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:53.679
It's available on GitHub.

00:42:53.679 --> 00:42:54.879
It's free and open source.

00:42:54.879 --> 00:42:56.399
It's a Quarter extension

00:42:56.399 --> 00:42:58.080
and I'm really super duper excited

00:42:58.080 --> 00:42:59.439
to see what you create

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:01.840
with this kind of tool.

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:03.600
Everything from educational content

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:05.199
for colleges and universities

00:43:05.199 --> 00:43:08.239
to interactive demonstrations

00:43:08.239 --> 00:43:10.479
of R packages in documentation.

00:43:12.080 --> 00:43:15.439
It also works with Python.

00:43:19.600 --> 00:43:21.600
It uses the PyDyed WebAssembly engine

00:43:21.600 --> 00:43:24.000
so you can also create exercises in Python too.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:25.040
And you can even share data

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:27.280
between WebAssembly and PyDyed,

00:43:27.280 --> 00:43:28.399
between Web on PyDyed

00:43:28.399 --> 00:43:30.159
if that is something you're interested in.

00:43:30.159 --> 00:43:32.239
Okay, I'm going to head off now.

00:43:32.239 --> 00:43:33.840
Thank you very much for listening.

00:43:33.840 --> 00:43:34.719
I'm going to hand you over

00:43:34.719 --> 00:43:36.000
to our next speaker, James.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:36.479
Thank you.

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:44.639
Thank you.

00:43:44.639 --> 00:43:46.000
Yesterday, I noticed

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:47.919
a particularly interesting sticker

00:43:47.919 --> 00:43:49.280
on Hadley's laptop.

00:43:49.280 --> 00:43:50.239
So, I asked him about it

00:43:50.800 --> 00:43:51.919
and he told me that it was

00:43:51.919 --> 00:43:54.719
for particularly strong contributors

00:43:54.719 --> 00:43:55.520
to the Tidyverse

00:43:56.159 --> 00:43:57.760
and then he didn't offer me one.

00:43:59.199 --> 00:44:01.600
Which isn't really surprising

00:44:01.600 --> 00:44:03.360
and in fact kind of begs the question,

00:44:03.360 --> 00:44:04.879
what am I doing up here?

00:44:05.520 --> 00:44:06.560
And if you find out,

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:07.600
please let me know.

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:10.159
I'd like to start today though

00:44:10.159 --> 00:44:11.280
by turning the clock back

00:44:11.280 --> 00:44:13.040
to an experience that we all likely had

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:14.639
at some point early in our journey,

00:44:14.639 --> 00:44:16.080
which was something like this.

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:18.000
For the very first time,

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:19.199
we opened up an environment

00:44:19.199 --> 00:44:22.000
or a tool like RStudio or VS Code

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.479
and we wrote some initial lines of R Python.

00:44:25.199 --> 00:44:26.479
Now, if you were like me,

00:44:26.479 --> 00:44:28.239
some of those initial lines of code

00:44:28.239 --> 00:44:30.320
read in some sort of local data source

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:31.840
and then allowed me to start exploring

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:32.800
that data object

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:34.080
using a new and exciting world

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:35.120
of open source tools.

00:44:35.919 --> 00:44:37.520
This was my very first introduction

00:44:37.520 --> 00:44:39.360
to this data science life cycle.

00:44:39.360 --> 00:44:41.199
This idea of bringing data

00:44:41.199 --> 00:44:42.479
into an environment,

00:44:42.479 --> 00:44:44.320
use tools to explore, visualize,

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:45.280
analyze, clean it up

00:44:45.280 --> 00:44:46.399
and then report out

00:44:46.399 --> 00:44:47.360
on the thing that I've learned.

00:44:48.159 --> 00:44:49.040
This period of my life

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:50.719
was a period of tremendous excitement.

00:44:50.719 --> 00:44:52.719
I still look back on this period of life

00:44:52.719 --> 00:44:53.679
and feel butterflies

00:44:53.679 --> 00:44:55.760
about how exciting it was to learn

00:44:55.760 --> 00:44:57.120
all that I was now capable of.

00:44:57.679 --> 00:44:58.479
And part of the reason

00:44:58.479 --> 00:44:59.679
that it was exciting at this point

00:44:59.679 --> 00:45:00.560
was because everything

00:45:00.560 --> 00:45:02.399
was very easily understood.

00:45:02.399 --> 00:45:03.360
The work that I was doing

00:45:03.360 --> 00:45:04.639
was all happening

00:45:04.639 --> 00:45:06.879
in the scope of my own little laptop.

00:45:06.879 --> 00:45:08.080
The tools I was using

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:09.360
and the data that I was accessing

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:11.280
were all available right in front of me,

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:12.800
easy to understand and think about.

00:45:13.679 --> 00:45:14.879
However, over time,

00:45:14.879 --> 00:45:16.320
things have changed a little bit.

00:45:16.320 --> 00:45:17.760
The data moved to a database.

00:45:17.760 --> 00:45:19.520
I had to figure out how to access that.

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:20.639
Then the tools I was using

00:45:20.639 --> 00:45:22.560
moved to some sort of cloud platform.

00:45:22.560 --> 00:45:23.840
Now the only gateway I had

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:25.679
was no longer some sort of process

00:45:25.679 --> 00:45:26.639
running locally,

00:45:26.639 --> 00:45:27.840
but rather a web browser

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:29.679
that I was using to access some service

00:45:29.679 --> 00:45:31.040
running somewhere else in the cloud.

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:32.879
Now, at the end of the day,

00:45:32.879 --> 00:45:34.080
I'm still doing this.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:35.520
I'm still accessing data.

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:36.560
I'm still working with it,

00:45:36.560 --> 00:45:37.280
understanding it

00:45:37.280 --> 00:45:38.159
and then communicating

00:45:38.159 --> 00:45:40.080
some sort of result from that data

00:45:40.080 --> 00:45:40.719
out to somebody

00:45:40.719 --> 00:45:42.159
who's invested in that result.

00:45:42.879 --> 00:45:44.159
But it can start to feel like

00:45:44.159 --> 00:45:44.800
to get there,

00:45:45.439 --> 00:45:46.479
I have to dig through

00:45:46.479 --> 00:45:48.719
an ever-growing pile of dirt.

00:45:48.719 --> 00:45:51.120
Now, we're fully capable people.

00:45:51.120 --> 00:45:54.080
We can dig in and get our hands dirty.

00:45:54.080 --> 00:45:55.120
But this is not the work

00:45:55.120 --> 00:45:56.159
that we want to be doing.

00:45:56.159 --> 00:45:57.760
Instead, we want to be working with data

00:45:58.479 --> 00:45:59.360
and we want to get there

00:45:59.360 --> 00:46:00.479
as quickly as possible.

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:02.320
Now, here at Posit,

00:46:02.320 --> 00:46:03.120
we've been hard at work

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:04.639
doing the best job that we can

00:46:04.639 --> 00:46:06.159
to clear this out of the way

00:46:06.159 --> 00:46:07.120
so that you can get back

00:46:07.120 --> 00:46:08.800
to doing the work that you know and love.

00:46:09.919 --> 00:46:10.959
One of the ways we've done that

00:46:10.959 --> 00:46:11.840
over the past year

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:12.959
has been through our partnerships

00:46:12.959 --> 00:46:14.479
with leading cloud platforms

00:46:14.479 --> 00:46:16.320
like Snowflake and Databricks.

00:46:16.320 --> 00:46:18.080
We've looked at our community

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:18.879
and the conversations

00:46:18.879 --> 00:46:20.239
that we have with each of you

00:46:20.239 --> 00:46:21.840
to determine ways that we can partner

00:46:21.840 --> 00:46:22.719
with these platforms

00:46:22.719 --> 00:46:24.320
to solve some of these unique challenges

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:25.199
that exist,

00:46:25.199 --> 00:46:26.320
particularly for those of you

00:46:26.320 --> 00:46:26.959
that are working

00:46:26.959 --> 00:46:28.800
in large enterprise organizations.

00:46:29.520 --> 00:46:32.080
We've identified kind of three key areas

00:46:32.080 --> 00:46:33.120
that we've been focused on.

00:46:33.760 --> 00:46:34.879
Infrastructure management,

00:46:35.600 --> 00:46:37.040
data access and control,

00:46:37.040 --> 00:46:38.479
and application deployment.

00:46:38.479 --> 00:46:39.760
I want to take a few minutes today

00:46:39.760 --> 00:46:40.800
to walk through some of the things

00:46:40.800 --> 00:46:41.360
that we've done

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:42.800
over the past several months

00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:44.159
to address some of the challenges

00:46:44.159 --> 00:46:44.800
that we've observed

00:46:44.800 --> 00:46:45.760
in each of these areas.

00:46:46.719 --> 00:46:48.239
Let's start with infrastructure management.

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:50.719
Now, most of you out here today

00:46:50.719 --> 00:46:52.320
are end users of Posit products,

00:46:52.320 --> 00:46:54.560
whether that's purely open source users

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:56.239
operating inside of the RStudio IDE

00:46:56.239 --> 00:46:57.280
in some environment

00:46:57.280 --> 00:46:58.000
or you're working

00:46:58.000 --> 00:46:59.919
as part of a large organization

00:46:59.919 --> 00:47:01.520
with access to our commercial tools.

00:47:02.479 --> 00:47:03.840
However, some of you,

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:04.639
either by choice

00:47:04.639 --> 00:47:06.320
or most of you likely by accident,

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:07.040
have found yourself

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:08.159
in an administrative role.

00:47:08.879 --> 00:47:10.159
This means that you're responsible

00:47:10.159 --> 00:47:12.159
for maintaining a set of infrastructure

00:47:12.159 --> 00:47:13.439
that other members of your team

00:47:13.439 --> 00:47:15.120
use to access Posit tools

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:16.399
or other tools in the cloud.

00:47:17.840 --> 00:47:19.360
As I speak with these individuals

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:20.399
almost every week,

00:47:20.399 --> 00:47:22.239
I hear some version of this request.

00:47:22.959 --> 00:47:24.879
We want everything to just be managed

00:47:24.879 --> 00:47:25.679
and done for us.

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:28.479
Now, I can understand this request.

00:47:29.040 --> 00:47:30.399
As enterprises grow

00:47:30.399 --> 00:47:32.000
in their infrastructure complexity,

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:33.280
the desire to simplify

00:47:33.520 --> 00:47:34.719
is increasing.

00:47:34.719 --> 00:47:36.320
And we see more and more organizations

00:47:36.320 --> 00:47:37.360
turning to cloud platforms

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:39.040
to try to solve this exact problem.

00:47:39.600 --> 00:47:40.959
And it's easy to understand why.

00:47:41.679 --> 00:47:42.560
If we take a look

00:47:42.560 --> 00:47:45.520
at the Posit Workbench documentation,

00:47:45.520 --> 00:47:47.520
you can see that it's rather complex

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:48.959
in the variety of different ways

00:47:48.959 --> 00:47:50.159
it can be configured,

00:47:50.159 --> 00:47:51.679
set up and administered.

00:47:51.679 --> 00:47:53.360
Now, this is not complexity

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:54.719
for complexity's sake.

00:47:54.719 --> 00:47:55.919
Rather, Workbench is designed

00:47:55.919 --> 00:47:56.959
to be highly flexible

00:47:56.959 --> 00:47:57.919
so that it can meet the needs

00:47:57.919 --> 00:47:59.520
of a variety of different organizations

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:00.639
based on size,

00:48:00.639 --> 00:48:01.679
security requirements

00:48:01.679 --> 00:48:02.320
and other needs.

00:48:03.280 --> 00:48:04.800
However, it can be difficult

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:05.919
to manage and maintain,

00:48:05.919 --> 00:48:07.439
particularly for smaller teams.

00:48:08.479 --> 00:48:09.040
One of the ways

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:10.560
that we've chosen to solve this

00:48:10.560 --> 00:48:12.080
is by partnering with organizations

00:48:12.080 --> 00:48:13.120
like Snowflake

00:48:13.120 --> 00:48:14.560
to provide Posit Workbench

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:15.360
as an application

00:48:15.360 --> 00:48:16.399
that's available

00:48:16.399 --> 00:48:17.760
through the Snowflake Marketplace.

00:48:18.560 --> 00:48:19.120
What this means

00:48:19.120 --> 00:48:20.560
is that existing Posit customers

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:22.399
can go to the Snowflake Marketplace,

00:48:22.399 --> 00:48:23.760
subscribe to this application,

00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:26.239
input their existing Posit license key,

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:29.360
update a few small configuration things

00:48:29.360 --> 00:48:30.399
and then provide users

00:48:30.399 --> 00:48:31.439
within their organization

00:48:31.439 --> 00:48:32.639
with access to a version

00:48:32.639 --> 00:48:33.760
of Posit Workbench

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:35.120
that's all running directly

00:48:35.120 --> 00:48:36.560
inside of their Snowflake infrastructure.

00:48:37.360 --> 00:48:38.639
This version of Posit Workbench

00:48:38.639 --> 00:48:40.159
will automatically be updated

00:48:40.159 --> 00:48:40.879
when new versions

00:48:40.879 --> 00:48:42.239
and new releases come out

00:48:42.239 --> 00:48:43.520
and it's a very low maintenance

00:48:43.520 --> 00:48:44.320
hands-off approach

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:45.919
to delivering the end result

00:48:45.919 --> 00:48:46.639
that users need.

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:48.399
And we're committed at Posit

00:48:48.399 --> 00:48:49.199
to continue to work

00:48:49.199 --> 00:48:50.959
with other cloud data platforms

00:48:50.959 --> 00:48:52.239
providing similar experience

00:48:52.239 --> 00:48:53.120
in other environments.

00:48:54.479 --> 00:48:56.080
Now, once your infrastructure

00:48:56.080 --> 00:48:57.600
is set up and configured,

00:48:57.600 --> 00:48:58.399
the next thing you need

00:48:58.399 --> 00:48:59.439
is access to the data.

00:49:00.239 --> 00:49:02.080
As an R user accessing local data

00:49:02.080 --> 00:49:03.040
or as a Python user,

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:03.919
accessing local data

00:49:03.919 --> 00:49:05.280
is typically pretty straightforward.

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:06.479
Like the example we saw

00:49:06.479 --> 00:49:07.439
at the very beginning,

00:49:07.439 --> 00:49:08.800
there's a whole series of commands,

00:49:08.800 --> 00:49:10.000
tools and packages

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:10.719
for reading data

00:49:10.719 --> 00:49:11.679
from a local data source,

00:49:11.679 --> 00:49:13.040
whether that's a CSV file

00:49:13.040 --> 00:49:13.760
or something else.

00:49:14.479 --> 00:49:16.320
However, once the data moves location

00:49:16.320 --> 00:49:18.320
and becomes part of an infrastructure

00:49:18.320 --> 00:49:19.280
that's more governed

00:49:19.280 --> 00:49:20.959
and more secure

00:49:20.959 --> 00:49:22.719
than what you would typically find locally,

00:49:22.719 --> 00:49:23.600
the way that we connect

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:25.040
starts to look like something like this.

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:27.439
This is an example of some R code

00:49:27.439 --> 00:49:28.800
used to access Databricks

00:49:28.800 --> 00:49:29.520
to read some data.

00:49:30.080 --> 00:49:31.199
There's a lot here.

00:49:31.280 --> 00:49:33.360
Now, it's not difficult to unpack.

00:49:33.360 --> 00:49:34.399
All of us are capable

00:49:34.399 --> 00:49:36.000
of writing code like this.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:37.679
But there's a lot of detail here

00:49:37.679 --> 00:49:39.280
that just provides opportunities

00:49:39.280 --> 00:49:40.000
for mistakes.

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:41.120
I need to know

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:42.719
what the ODBC driver is called.

00:49:42.719 --> 00:49:43.520
I need to understand

00:49:43.520 --> 00:49:45.120
what these different arguments are.

00:49:45.120 --> 00:49:46.639
And perhaps most critically,

00:49:46.639 --> 00:49:47.280
I need to make sure

00:49:47.280 --> 00:49:48.479
that I'm accessing this

00:49:48.479 --> 00:49:49.760
in a secure way

00:49:49.760 --> 00:49:51.199
that meets the security requirements

00:49:51.199 --> 00:49:52.000
of my organization,

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:53.040
whether that's through a username

00:49:53.040 --> 00:49:53.760
and password

00:49:53.760 --> 00:49:55.280
or more often than not,

00:49:55.280 --> 00:49:56.879
some form of a security token

00:49:56.879 --> 00:49:58.479
that I don't have to remember,

00:49:58.479 --> 00:49:59.040
but I have to keep

00:49:59.040 --> 00:50:00.320
in a super secret location

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:01.439
and update every 30 days.

00:50:02.239 --> 00:50:03.439
That can become a challenge.

00:50:04.159 --> 00:50:05.040
So we've worked hard

00:50:05.040 --> 00:50:05.919
over the past several months

00:50:05.919 --> 00:50:07.679
to take this amount of work

00:50:07.679 --> 00:50:08.639
and turn it into something

00:50:08.639 --> 00:50:09.520
that looks more like this.

00:50:10.879 --> 00:50:12.879
This approach dramatically simplifies

00:50:12.879 --> 00:50:13.919
our ability to connect

00:50:13.919 --> 00:50:15.679
to external data sources.

00:50:15.679 --> 00:50:16.320
Because again,

00:50:16.320 --> 00:50:17.919
until we have access to the data,

00:50:17.919 --> 00:50:19.600
the real work hasn't really started yet.

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:21.199
We've accomplished this

00:50:21.199 --> 00:50:22.800
in a couple of different ways.

00:50:22.800 --> 00:50:24.080
One is through our contributions

00:50:24.080 --> 00:50:26.239
to the open source ODBC R package

00:50:26.239 --> 00:50:28.000
with functions like Databricks.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:28.959
And there's also a function

00:50:28.959 --> 00:50:30.080
called Snowflake

00:50:30.080 --> 00:50:31.600
that facilitate easy connections

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:32.879
to these external resources.

00:50:33.439 --> 00:50:34.239
These functions are part

00:50:34.239 --> 00:50:35.280
of the open source package

00:50:35.280 --> 00:50:36.320
and are available to anyone.

00:50:37.120 --> 00:50:38.639
We've also made some adjustments

00:50:38.639 --> 00:50:40.159
on the Posit Workbench side

00:50:40.159 --> 00:50:42.320
to make it much easier for individuals

00:50:42.320 --> 00:50:43.120
to gain access

00:50:43.120 --> 00:50:44.560
to these backend data resources.

00:50:45.679 --> 00:50:47.280
Posit Workbench users today

00:50:47.280 --> 00:50:48.159
can now not only sign

00:50:48.159 --> 00:50:49.040
into Posit Workbench

00:50:49.040 --> 00:50:50.080
and start a new session

00:50:50.080 --> 00:50:51.760
and decide whether they want to use

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:52.959
VS Code or RStudio

00:50:52.959 --> 00:50:54.639
or any number of other tools.

00:50:54.639 --> 00:50:56.399
They can also choose to sign in

00:50:56.399 --> 00:50:57.439
to their Databricks account

00:50:57.439 --> 00:50:58.479
or their Snowflake account.

00:50:59.120 --> 00:50:59.679
Once they've gone

00:50:59.679 --> 00:51:00.719
through this sign-in process,

00:51:00.719 --> 00:51:01.439
which will just follow

00:51:01.439 --> 00:51:03.040
whatever the typical sign-in process

00:51:03.040 --> 00:51:04.159
is within your organization,

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:05.679
Posit Workbench

00:51:05.679 --> 00:51:07.520
then will manage credentials

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:09.120
for that data connection

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:09.919
on your behalf.

00:51:10.639 --> 00:51:11.600
This means you no longer

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:13.120
have to think about access tokens,

00:51:13.120 --> 00:51:14.399
passwords, how to manage those,

00:51:14.399 --> 00:51:15.120
how to pass those

00:51:15.120 --> 00:51:16.479
into the connection string.

00:51:16.479 --> 00:51:18.399
All that is taken care of for you

00:51:18.399 --> 00:51:19.439
and you can get in

00:51:19.439 --> 00:51:20.479
and immediately connect

00:51:20.479 --> 00:51:21.679
to these data resources.

00:51:22.399 --> 00:51:23.919
Now, this doesn't just work for ODBC,

00:51:23.919 --> 00:51:25.439
although it works very well there.

00:51:25.439 --> 00:51:26.080
You'll also notice

00:51:26.080 --> 00:51:27.040
that it works for tools

00:51:27.040 --> 00:51:27.840
like SparklyR

00:51:27.840 --> 00:51:29.439
and interacting with Spark

00:51:29.439 --> 00:51:30.479
and Databricks.

00:51:30.479 --> 00:51:32.320
And it also works inside of VS Code

00:51:32.320 --> 00:51:33.760
for a number of Python frameworks

00:51:33.760 --> 00:51:35.439
and SDKs that have been provided

00:51:35.439 --> 00:51:36.639
by platforms like Snowflake

00:51:36.639 --> 00:51:37.199
and Databricks

00:51:37.199 --> 00:51:38.879
as well as their respective

00:51:38.879 --> 00:51:40.000
VS Code extensions.

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:44.399
Okay, so I've got access to the data.

00:51:44.399 --> 00:51:45.919
Now I'm able to do what I want to do.

00:51:45.919 --> 00:51:46.879
I explore the data.

00:51:46.879 --> 00:51:48.399
I understand what it's teaching me.

00:51:48.399 --> 00:51:49.600
I finally arrive at something

00:51:49.600 --> 00:51:50.239
that I want to share.

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:51.919
So what do I share?

00:51:53.040 --> 00:51:53.679
In many cases,

00:51:53.679 --> 00:51:55.199
we see people share emails,

00:51:55.199 --> 00:51:56.320
PowerPoint presentations,

00:51:56.959 --> 00:51:58.639
static plots, documents.

00:51:58.639 --> 00:51:59.840
But more and more frequently,

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:01.199
we're observing that users

00:52:01.199 --> 00:52:03.199
are creating dynamic dashboards

00:52:03.199 --> 00:52:05.040
and interactive web applications

00:52:05.040 --> 00:52:06.320
that allow end users

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:07.520
and business users

00:52:07.520 --> 00:52:08.719
to discover, explore,

00:52:08.719 --> 00:52:10.159
and arrive at their own conclusions.

00:52:10.879 --> 00:52:12.320
PositConnect makes it really easy

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:13.360
to share and deploy

00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:14.479
these kinds of applications

00:52:14.479 --> 00:52:15.919
across your organization.

00:52:15.919 --> 00:52:17.439
So I can build a dashboard

00:52:17.439 --> 00:52:18.959
that I share with the rest of my company.

00:52:19.840 --> 00:52:21.760
However, as soon as I make this transition

00:52:21.760 --> 00:52:23.120
from saying I've built something

00:52:23.120 --> 00:52:24.719
to I want to share something,

00:52:24.719 --> 00:52:25.840
I once again have to think

00:52:25.840 --> 00:52:26.719
about authentication.

00:52:27.280 --> 00:52:28.560
And the problem has gotten bigger

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:29.679
because now I'm not just thinking

00:52:29.679 --> 00:52:30.959
about my own authentication

00:52:30.959 --> 00:52:32.639
and how do I access the data.

00:52:32.639 --> 00:52:33.919
Now I'm thinking about

00:52:33.919 --> 00:52:34.800
how should everyone

00:52:34.800 --> 00:52:36.239
who visits this application

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:37.679
access the data.

00:52:38.879 --> 00:52:40.479
In a world where data security

00:52:40.479 --> 00:52:42.080
is of highest importance,

00:52:42.080 --> 00:52:43.760
the last thing I want to do

00:52:43.760 --> 00:52:45.120
is unintentionally publish

00:52:45.120 --> 00:52:46.239
an application

00:52:46.239 --> 00:52:47.360
that gives someone else

00:52:47.360 --> 00:52:48.399
unauthorized access

00:52:48.399 --> 00:52:49.360
to data they should not

00:52:49.360 --> 00:52:50.320
otherwise be able to see.

00:52:51.520 --> 00:52:54.239
Now, this is not a new problem necessarily.

00:52:54.239 --> 00:52:55.520
In fact, there are well-established

00:52:55.679 --> 00:52:56.719
patterns for how to approach this.

00:52:56.719 --> 00:52:57.520
One of them is to use

00:52:57.520 --> 00:52:58.879
some sort of access token

00:52:58.879 --> 00:53:00.639
attached to a service account.

00:53:00.639 --> 00:53:01.919
So I create some sort of account

00:53:01.919 --> 00:53:03.679
inside of Databricks, for example,

00:53:03.679 --> 00:53:04.560
or Snowflake.

00:53:04.560 --> 00:53:05.520
I say here's the permissions

00:53:05.520 --> 00:53:06.159
for that account.

00:53:06.159 --> 00:53:07.040
I generate a token

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:07.919
and then I input that

00:53:07.919 --> 00:53:09.360
into my Connect product,

00:53:09.360 --> 00:53:10.479
into my dashboard

00:53:10.479 --> 00:53:11.360
so that it will use

00:53:11.360 --> 00:53:12.479
that same credential set

00:53:12.479 --> 00:53:13.520
whenever somebody

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:14.560
visits the application.

00:53:15.439 --> 00:53:17.120
This pattern works very well,

00:53:17.120 --> 00:53:18.000
but it really has

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:19.199
two distinct limitations.

00:53:19.840 --> 00:53:21.360
One is everybody

00:53:21.360 --> 00:53:22.399
visiting this dashboard

00:53:22.399 --> 00:53:23.919
will see the same data

00:53:23.919 --> 00:53:25.199
regardless of what

00:53:25.199 --> 00:53:27.360
their specific permission set is.

00:53:27.360 --> 00:53:29.280
They will see data governed by

00:53:29.280 --> 00:53:30.000
the permission set

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:31.280
of the service account I've set up.

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:33.760
The other problem though

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:35.280
is that if the number of applications

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:36.639
I build grows,

00:53:37.520 --> 00:53:39.120
the amount of service accounts

00:53:39.120 --> 00:53:40.159
and access tokens

00:53:40.159 --> 00:53:42.399
I'm responsible for also grows.

00:53:42.399 --> 00:53:43.360
And now I'm spending

00:53:43.360 --> 00:53:44.080
far more time

00:53:44.080 --> 00:53:45.360
worrying about data access

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:46.159
and security from my

00:53:46.159 --> 00:53:47.360
deployed applications

00:53:47.360 --> 00:53:48.320
than I am building

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:49.120
and distributing

00:53:49.120 --> 00:53:51.040
and creating new applications.

00:53:52.639 --> 00:53:53.679
We're excited to announce

00:53:53.679 --> 00:53:55.199
that starting last week,

00:53:55.199 --> 00:53:56.239
this is all gone.

00:53:56.959 --> 00:53:58.000
What we've now introduced

00:53:58.000 --> 00:53:58.800
in Posit Connect

00:53:58.800 --> 00:53:59.600
is native support

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:00.399
for authentication

00:54:00.399 --> 00:54:01.679
into Databricks and Snowflake

00:54:01.679 --> 00:54:02.320
just like we have

00:54:02.320 --> 00:54:03.280
in Posit Workbench.

00:54:03.919 --> 00:54:04.959
What this means is now

00:54:04.959 --> 00:54:05.760
instead of configuring

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:06.959
an access token,

00:54:06.959 --> 00:54:08.959
I can come into Posit Connect

00:54:08.959 --> 00:54:09.919
and specify that

00:54:09.919 --> 00:54:11.520
I want to make sure that

00:54:11.520 --> 00:54:13.199
whoever visits this application

00:54:13.199 --> 00:54:15.280
signs in to their Databricks

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:16.159
or Snowflake account.

00:54:16.879 --> 00:54:18.000
Then as a viewer,

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:19.120
if I come to the application,

00:54:19.120 --> 00:54:20.080
I'll see something like this.

00:54:20.800 --> 00:54:21.600
This is my view.

00:54:22.320 --> 00:54:23.040
But if I send this

00:54:23.040 --> 00:54:23.919
to somebody else

00:54:23.919 --> 00:54:24.800
and say I want you to log

00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:26.239
into this application,

00:54:26.239 --> 00:54:27.280
they'll first be prompted

00:54:27.280 --> 00:54:27.840
to log into their

00:54:27.840 --> 00:54:28.639
Snowflake account.

00:54:29.199 --> 00:54:29.919
And once they've logged

00:54:29.919 --> 00:54:31.199
in their Snowflake account,

00:54:31.199 --> 00:54:32.879
they'll see the same application

00:54:32.879 --> 00:54:34.719
but with their own unique view

00:54:34.719 --> 00:54:35.760
powered by the permissions

00:54:35.760 --> 00:54:36.639
they've been assigned

00:54:36.639 --> 00:54:37.520
inside of Snowflake.

00:54:38.399 --> 00:54:39.840
This means I don't have to worry

00:54:39.840 --> 00:54:40.800
about who has access

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:41.760
to what data.

00:54:41.760 --> 00:54:43.199
Instead, I can build something

00:54:43.199 --> 00:54:44.159
and share it

00:54:44.159 --> 00:54:45.600
and then anyone who accesses it

00:54:45.600 --> 00:54:46.959
will have access to the data

00:54:46.959 --> 00:54:48.560
they should be able to see

00:54:48.560 --> 00:54:49.280
based on the permission

00:54:49.280 --> 00:54:49.919
that have been set

00:54:49.919 --> 00:54:51.199
within the database.

00:54:51.199 --> 00:54:52.560
This works today for Snowflake

00:54:52.639 --> 00:54:53.439
and Databricks

00:54:53.439 --> 00:54:54.320
and we're actually looking

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:55.439
at other ways that we can continue

00:54:55.439 --> 00:54:56.879
to expand this functionality.

00:54:58.479 --> 00:54:59.600
Now, at the end of the day,

00:55:00.239 --> 00:55:01.280
our mission at Posit,

00:55:01.280 --> 00:55:02.639
as Hadley stated earlier,

00:55:02.639 --> 00:55:04.399
is to create open source software

00:55:05.199 --> 00:55:06.159
for data science,

00:55:06.159 --> 00:55:07.280
scientific research,

00:55:07.280 --> 00:55:08.479
and technical communication.

00:55:09.120 --> 00:55:10.639
Now, one of our goals

00:55:10.639 --> 00:55:11.840
and my personal goal

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:13.199
is to make sure that

00:55:13.199 --> 00:55:14.000
regardless of whether

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:15.919
you're operating on the desktop

00:55:16.800 --> 00:55:18.479
or you're operating in the cloud

00:55:19.040 --> 00:55:20.639
or anywhere in between,

00:55:20.639 --> 00:55:22.000
you have the ability to do that

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:22.560
in an environment

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:23.919
that feels comfortable

00:55:23.919 --> 00:55:25.040
and familiar

00:55:25.040 --> 00:55:25.919
and is immediately

00:55:25.919 --> 00:55:26.959
and easily accessible.

00:55:28.879 --> 00:55:29.840
If you'd like to learn more

00:55:29.840 --> 00:55:30.479
about some of the things

00:55:30.479 --> 00:55:31.520
that we've discussed this morning,

00:55:31.520 --> 00:55:32.719
our commercial products,

00:55:32.719 --> 00:55:34.000
our partnerships with organizations

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:35.360
like Snowflake and Databricks

00:55:35.360 --> 00:55:36.560
or anything else,

00:55:36.560 --> 00:55:37.600
again, feel free to visit us

00:55:37.600 --> 00:55:38.159
in the lounge,

00:55:38.159 --> 00:55:38.800
which can be found

00:55:38.800 --> 00:55:39.600
right outside the doors

00:55:39.600 --> 00:55:40.639
in the back of this room.

00:55:40.639 --> 00:55:41.280
There'll be members

00:55:41.280 --> 00:55:42.479
from the Posit product teams there

00:55:42.479 --> 00:55:43.679
happy to answer questions

00:55:43.679 --> 00:55:45.199
and you can find me there as well.

00:55:45.199 --> 00:55:45.840
And with that,

00:55:45.840 --> 00:55:46.879
please join me in welcoming

00:55:46.879 --> 00:55:48.000
the one and only Hadley

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:48.719
back on stage.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:58.239
Thanks, James.

00:55:58.239 --> 00:56:00.239
So if you've been paying attention

00:56:00.239 --> 00:56:01.600
to kind of data science

00:56:01.600 --> 00:56:02.239
on the Internet

00:56:02.239 --> 00:56:04.000
or some form of social media,

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:04.959
you might be wondering

00:56:04.959 --> 00:56:05.520
that there's something

00:56:05.520 --> 00:56:06.800
we didn't talk about today,

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:09.040
and that's Positron.

00:56:09.040 --> 00:56:11.919
So Positron is a new multilingual IDE

00:56:11.919 --> 00:56:13.520
that we've been working on at Posit.

00:56:14.320 --> 00:56:15.600
The goal is to take

00:56:15.600 --> 00:56:17.120
all of the things that you love

00:56:17.120 --> 00:56:18.639
about our studio

00:56:18.639 --> 00:56:20.719
and build them

00:56:20.800 --> 00:56:22.399
on top of a new modern platform,

00:56:22.399 --> 00:56:24.000
build on top of VS code.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:26.399
So as well as R and Python,

00:56:26.399 --> 00:56:28.320
we can continue to support data science

00:56:28.320 --> 00:56:29.439
in whatever languages

00:56:29.439 --> 00:56:30.639
come along in the future.

00:56:31.199 --> 00:56:32.000
If you'd like to hear

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:33.679
more about Positron,

00:56:33.679 --> 00:56:34.320
you're going to hear

00:56:34.320 --> 00:56:35.520
from the entire Positron

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:36.719
development team

00:56:36.719 --> 00:56:38.159
in the next session

00:56:38.159 --> 00:56:39.520
after this break

00:56:39.520 --> 00:56:40.879
in Columbia A&B.

00:56:42.800 --> 00:56:43.919
So with that, again,

00:56:43.919 --> 00:56:46.080
thank you for joining us

00:56:46.080 --> 00:56:47.120
all at PositConf

00:56:47.120 --> 00:56:49.040
in person and online.

00:56:49.040 --> 00:56:49.600
Please enjoy

00:56:49.600 --> 00:56:50.560
the rest of the conference.

00:56:50.719 --> 00:56:54.879
Thank you.

